{
  "texts": [
    "This typically reflects more realistic scenarios where certain classes are more likely to be confused with others (e.g., automobiles and trucks).On top of that, we also consider the instance-dependent label noise assumption, which has gained increasing attention in recent years, as it better simulates real-world scenarios.",
    "This assumption extends the previous setting by positing that the corruption process depends not only on the true label y and corrupted label ŷ, but also on the input sample x [43].",
    "C. Active Passive Loss FunctionsMa et al. [14] proposed the concept of normalized loss functions, where a given loss function L can be normalized as follows:L norm (f (x), y; L) = L(f (x), y) K k=1 L(f (x), k).",
    "(2)This simple normalization operation can make any loss function robust to noisy labels.",
    "For instance, the Normalized Cross Entropy (NCE) is defined as (note CE amounts to the negative log likelihood):L NCE (f (x), y) = K k=1 q(k|x)(-log p(k|x)) K j=1 K k=1 q(y = j|x) log p(k|x)."
  ]
